<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1436,325,709]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis box="[199,297,505,529]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Remarks</emphasis>
: In general, the tegmen of 
<taxonomicName box="[612,762,505,529]" class="Insecta" family="Issidae" genus="Gergithus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tessellatus">
<emphasis box="[612,762,505,529]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">G. tessellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is black with 
<number box="[928,956,505,529]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="10.0">10</number>
green marks (faded to a yellow colour in dried specimens), arranged 
<number box="[465,511,541,565]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="1.3">1, 3</number>
, 
<number box="[525,568,541,565]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="4.2">4, 2</number>
from base to apex by original description, but in our examination, the body colour and marks on the tegmen of some specimens have great variation: the tegmen may be black with some yellow spots joined with each other (
<figureCitation box="[526,661,613,637]" captionStart="FIGURES 65 – 73" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1940,1963]" captionTargetBox="[158,1428,617,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,605,1929]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 65 – 73 Gergithus tessellatus Matsumura, 1916 65, 68, 71. adult, dorsal view; 66, 69, 72. adult, lateral view; 67, 70, 73. frons and clypeus. Scale bars = 1 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/211937/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Figs. 
<number box="[589,661,613,637]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="65.66">65, 66</number>
</figureCitation>
), or the black tegmen may only have scattered yellow spots (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 65 – 73" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1940,1963]" captionTargetBox="[158,1428,617,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,605,1929]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 65 – 73 Gergithus tessellatus Matsumura, 1916 65, 68, 71. adult, dorsal view; 66, 69, 72. adult, lateral view; 67, 70, 73. frons and clypeus. Scale bars = 1 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/211937/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Figs. 
<number pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="68.69">68, 69</number>
</figureCitation>
), or the body may be dark brown with irregular stripes on the tegmen (
<figureCitation box="[974,1111,649,673]" captionStart="FIGURES 65 – 73" captionStartId="15.[151,264,1940,1963]" captionTargetBox="[158,1428,617,1916]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,605,1929]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 65 – 73 Gergithus tessellatus Matsumura, 1916 65, 68, 71. adult, dorsal view; 66, 69, 72. adult, lateral view; 67, 70, 73. frons and clypeus. Scale bars = 1 mm" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/211937/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Figs. 
<number box="[1037,1111,649,673]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="71.72">71, 72</number>
</figureCitation>
). All of specimens examined have the same male genital characters except the features described above. We treat them as the same species here.
</paragraph>
